# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-automation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Originally written by Michael DeHaan in 2012, and acquired by Red Hat in 2015, Ansible is designed to configure both Unix-like systems and Microsoft Windows.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Ansible is agentless, relying on temporary remote connections via SSH or Windows Remote Management which allows PowerShell execution.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] The Ansible control node runs on most Unix-like systems that are able to run Python, including Windows with Windows Subsystem for Linux installed.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] System configuration is defined in part by using its own declarative language.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] The term "ansible" was coined by Ursula K.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Le Guin in her 1966 novel *Rocannon's World*, and refers to fictional instantaneous communication systems.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] The Ansible tool was developed by Michael DeHaan, the author of the provisioning server application Cobbler and co-author of the Fedora Unified Network Controller (Func) framework for remote administration.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] (originally AnsibleWorks, Inc.) was the company founded in 2013 by DeHaan, Timothy Gerla, and Saïd Ziouani to commercially support and sponsor Ansible.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Red Hat acquired Ansible in October 2015.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Ansible helps to manage multiple machines by selecting portions of Ansible's inventory stored in simple plain text files.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] The inventory is configurable, and target machine inventory can be sourced dynamically or from cloud-based sources in different formats (YAML, INI).
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Sensitive data can be stored in encrypted files using Ansible Vault since 2014.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] In contrast with other popular configuration-management software — such as Chef, Puppet, Salt and CFEngine — Ansible uses an *agentless* architecture, with Ansible software not normally running or even installed on the controlled node.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Instead, Ansible orchestrates a node by installing and running *modules* on the node temporarily via SSH.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] For the duration of an orchestration task, a process running the module communicates with the controlling machine with a JSON-based protocol via its standard input and output.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] When Ansible is not managing a node, it does not consume resources on the node because no daemons are run or software installed.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Ansible requires Python to be installed on all managing machines, including pip package manager along with configuration-management software and its dependent packages.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Managed network devices require no extra dependencies and are agentless.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] The control node (master host) is intended to manage (orchestrate) target machines (nodes termed as "inventory", see below).
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Control nodes can be run from Linux and Unix-like operating systems (including MacOS); Windows OSs are only supported through the Windows Subsystem for Linux.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Ansible does not require a single controlling machine for orchestration, ensuring that disaster recovery is simple.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Nodes are managed by the controlling node over SSH.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Modules are mostly standalone and can be written in a standard scripting language (such as Python, Perl, Ruby, Bash, etc.).
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] One of the guiding goals of modules is idempotency, which means that even if an operation is repeated multiple times (e.g., upon recovery from an outage), it will always place the system into the same state.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Location of target nodes is specified through inventory configuration lists (INI or YAML formatted) located at `/etc/ansible/hosts` (on Linux).
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] The configuration file lists either the IP address or hostname of each node that is accessible by Ansible.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] In addition, nodes can be assigned to groups.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] This configuration file specifies three nodes: the first node is specified by an IP address, and the latter two nodes are specified by hostnames.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Additionally, the latter two nodes are grouped under the `webservers` group.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Ansible can also use a custom *Dynamic Inventory* script, which can dynamically pull data from a different system, and supports groups of groups.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Playbooks are YAML files that store lists of tasks for repeated executions on managed nodes.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Each Playbook maps (associates) a group of hosts to a set of roles.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Each role is represented by calls to Ansible tasks.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] The Ansible Automation Platform (AAP) is a REST API, web service, and web-based interface (application) designed to make Ansible more accessible to people with a wide range of IT skillsets.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] It is a platform composed of multiple components including developer tooling, an operations interface, as well as an Automation Mesh to enable automation tasks at scale across data centers.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] AAP is a commercial product supported by Red Hat, Inc. but derived from 17+ upstream open source projects including the AWX upstream project (formerly Ansible Tower), which has been open source since September 2017.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] There also is another open source alternative to Tower, Semaphore, written in Go.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Control machines have to be a Linux/Unix host (for example BSD, CentOS, Debian, macOS, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, SUSE Linux Enterprise, Ubuntu), and Python 2.7 or 3.5 is required.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Managed nodes, if they are Unix-like, must have Python 2.4 or later.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] For managed nodes with Python 2.5 or earlier, the `python-simplejson` package is also required.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Since version 1.7, Ansible can also manage Windows nodes.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] In this case, native PowerShell remoting supported by the WS-Management protocol is used instead of SSH.
[src:network-automation/ansible-software] Ansible can deploy to bare metal hosts, virtual machines, and cloud environments.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:network-automation/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] In July 2004, Dustin Snell launched Network Automation, Inc. in Los Angeles, California.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] In September 2012, after two years as Chief Software Architect, Snell resumed his role as CEO.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] In April 2014, the company was acquired by Minneapolis, Minnesota–based HelpSystems, an IT software company offering solutions in the areas of systems and network management, business intelligence, security and compliance, for IBM i, Unix, Linux and Windows environments.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] The company’s main products were AutoMate and AutoMate BPA Server, which ran on Windows operating systems.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] The products were designed to simplify repetitive IT tasks via a drag and drop GUI interface, without requiring end user coding.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] Functions included job scheduling, automated FTP, batch processing, automated backups, scripting, automated testing, event log monitoring and automated reporting.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] 2012 enhancements included support for Windows Azure and Amazon Web Services.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] Third party applications such as Microsoft CRM could also be integrated.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] Advanced Systems Concepts, Inc. was a California court case decided in favor of Network Automation on March 8, 2011.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] The Ninth Circuit Court verdict protected the rights of companies to use strategic keywords in Internet search advertising.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] AutoMate won awards from Windows IT Pro, CNET and NetworkWorld and was named as the "Best Scripting Tool" by *Redmondmag*.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] The company was named to the 2009, 2011 and 2012 Inc.
[src:network-automation/network-automation] 5000 as one of the fastest growing software companies in the US.
[src:network-automation/network-management] A number of applications and protocols exist to support network and network device management.
[src:network-automation/network-management] Network management allows IT professionals to monitor network components within a large network area.
[src:network-automation/network-management] Access methods include the SNMP, command-line interface (CLI), custom XML, CMIP, Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), Transaction Language 1 (TL1), CORBA, NETCONF, RESTCONF and the Java Management Extensions (JMX).
[src:network-automation/network-management] Schemas include the Structure of Management Information (SMI), YANG, WBEM, the Common Information Model (CIM Schema), and MTOSI amongst others.
[src:network-automation/network-management] Effective network management can provide positive strategic impacts.
[src:network-automation/network-management] For example, in the case of developing an infrastructure, providing participants with some interactive space allows them to collaborate with each other, thereby promoting overall benefits.
[src:network-automation/network-management] At the same time, the value of network management to the strategic network is also affected by the relationship between participants.
[src:network-automation/network-management] Active participation, interaction and collaboration can make them more trusting of each other and enhance cohesion.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] In telecommunications, **provisioning** involves the process of preparing and equipping a network to allow it to provide new services to its users.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] In National Security/Emergency Preparedness telecommunications services, *"provisioning"* equates to *"initiation"* and includes altering the state of an existing priority service or capability.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] The concept of **network provisioning** or **service mediation**, mostly used in the telecommunication industry, refers to the provisioning of the customer's services to the network elements, which are various equipment connected in that network communication system.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Generally in telephony provisioning this is accomplished with network management database table mappings.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] It requires the existence of networking equipment and depends on network planning and design.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] In a modern signal infrastructure employing information technology (IT) at all levels, there is no possible distinction between telecommunications services and "higher level" infrastructure.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Accordingly, provisioning configures any required systems, provides users with access to data and technology resources, and refers to all enterprise-level information-resource management involved.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] As its core, the provisioning process monitors access rights and privileges to ensure the security of an enterprise's resources and user privacy.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] As a secondary responsibility, it ensures compliance and minimizes the vulnerability of systems to penetration and abuse.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] As a tertiary responsibility, it tries to reduce the amount of custom configuration using boot image control and other methods that radically reduce the number of different configurations involved.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Discussion of provisioning often appears in the context of virtualization, orchestration, utility computing, cloud computing, and open-configuration concepts and projects.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Once provisioning has taken place, the process of SysOpping ensures the maintenance of services to the expected standards.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Provisioning thus refers only to the setup or startup part of the service operation, and SysOpping to the ongoing support.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] The services which are assigned to the customer in the customer relationship management (CRM) have to be provisioned on the network element which is enabling the service and allows the customer to actually use the service.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] The relation between a service configured in the CRM and a service on the network elements is not necessarily a one-to-one relationship; for example, services like Microsoft Media Server (mms://) can be enabled by more than one network element.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] During the provisioning, the service mediation device translates the service and the corresponding parameters of the service to one or more services/parameters on the network elements involved.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] The algorithm used to translate a system service into network services is called **provisioning logic**.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Electronic invoice feeds from your carriers can be automatically downloaded directly into the core of the telecom expense management (TEM) software and it will immediately conduct an audit of each single line item charge all the way down to the User Support and Operations Center (USOC) level.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] The provisioning software will capture each circuit number provided by all of your carriers and if billing occurs outside of the contracted rate an exception rule will trigger a red flag and notify the pre-established staff member to review the billing error.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Server provisioning is a set of actions to prepare a server with appropriate systems, data and software, and make it ready for network operation.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] By auditing the system, you ensure OVAL compliance with limit vulnerability, ensure compliance, or install patches.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] After these actions, you restart the system and load the new software.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] This makes the system ready for operation.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Typically an internet service provider (ISP) or network operations center will perform these tasks to a well-defined set of parameters, for example, a boot image that the organization has approved and which uses software it has license to.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Many instances of such a boot image create a virtual dedicated host.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] There are many software products available to automate the provisioning of servers, services and end-user devices.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Examples: BMC Bladelogic Server Automation, HP Server Automation, IBM Tivoli Provisioning Manager, Redhat Kickstart, xCAT, HP Insight CMU, etc.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Middleware and applications can be installed either when the operating system is installed or afterwards by using an Application Service Automation tool.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Further questions are addressed in academia such as when provisioning should be issued and how many servers are needed in multi-tier, or multi-service applications.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] In cloud computing, servers may be provisioned via a web user interface or an application programming interface (API).
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] One of the unique things about cloud computing is how rapidly and easily this can be done.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Monitoring software can be used to trigger automatic provisioning when existing resources become too heavily stressed.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] In short, server provisioning configures servers based on resource requirements.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] The use of a hardware or software component (e.g. single/dual processor, RAM, HDD, RAID Controller, a number of LAN cards, applications, OS, etc.) depends on the functionality of the server, such as ISP, virtualization, NOS, or voice processing.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Server redundancy depends on the availability of servers in the organization.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Critical applications have less downtime when using cluster servers, RAID, or a mirroring system.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Service used by most larger-scale centers in part to avoid this.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Additional **resource provisioning** may be done per service.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] There are several software on the market for server provisioning such as Cobbler or HP Intelligent Provisioning.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] User provisioning refers to the creation, maintenance and deactivation of user objects and user attributes, as they exist in one or more systems, directories or applications, in response to automated or interactive business processes.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] User provisioning software may include one or more of the following processes: change propagation, self-service workflow, consolidated user administration, delegated user administration, and federated change control.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] User objects may represent employees, contractors, vendors, partners, customers or other recipients of a service.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Services may include electronic mail, inclusion in a published user directory, access to a database, access to a network or mainframe, etc.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] User provisioning is a type of identity management software, particularly useful within organizations, where users may be represented by multiple objects on multiple systems and multiple instances.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] On-demand self-service is described by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) as an essential characteristic of cloud computing.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] The self-service nature of cloud computing lets end users obtain and remove cloud services―including applications, the infrastructure supporting the applications, and configuration― themselves without requiring the assistance of an IT staff member.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] The automatic self-servicing may target different application goals and constraints (e.g. deadlines and cost), as well as handling different application architectures (e.g., bags-of-tasks and workflows).
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Cloud users can obtain cloud services through a cloud service catalog or a self-service portal.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Because business users can obtain and configure cloud services themselves, this means IT staff can be more productive and gives them more time to manage cloud infrastructures.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] One downside of cloud service provisioning is that it is not instantaneous.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] A cloud virtual machine (VM) can be acquired at any time by the user, but it may take up to several minutes for the acquired VM to be ready to use.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] The VM startup time is dependent on factors, such as image size, VM type, data center location, and number of VMs.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Cloud providers have different VM startup performance.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Mobile subscriber provisioning refers to the setting up of new services, such as GPRS, MMS and Instant Messaging for an existing subscriber of a mobile phone network, and any gateways to standard Internet chat or mail services.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] The network operator typically sends these settings to the subscriber's handset using SMS text services or HTML, and less commonly WAP, depending on what the mobile operating systems can accept.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] A general example of provisioning is with data services.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] A mobile user who is using his or her device for voice calling may wish to switch to data services in order to read emails or browse the Internet.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] The mobile device's services are "provisioned" and thus the user is able to stay connected through push emails and other features of smartphone services.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Device management systems can benefit end-users by incorporating plug-and-play data services, supporting whatever device the end-user is using..
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Such a platform can automatically detect devices in the network, sending them settings for immediate and continued usability.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] The process is fully automated, keeping the history of used devices and sending settings only to subscriber devices which were not previously set.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] One method of managing mobile updates is to filter IMEI/IMSI pairs.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Some operators report activity of 50 over-the-air settings update files per second.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] This refers to delivering mobile content, such as mobile internet to a mobile phone, agnostic of the features of said device.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] These may include operating system type and versions, Java version, browser version, screen form factors, audio capabilities, language settings and many other characteristics.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] As of April 2006, an estimated 5,000 permutations were relevant.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Mobile content provisioning facilitates a common user experience, though delivered on widely different handsets.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] Provisioning devices involves delivering configuration data and policy settings to the mobile devices from a central point – Mobile device management system tools.
[src:network-automation/provisioning-technology] When getting a customer online, the client system must be configured.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SDN was commonly associated with the OpenFlow protocol for remote communication with network plane elements to determine the path of network packets across network switches since OpenFlow's emergence in 2011.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] However, since 2012, proprietary systems have also used the term.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] These include Cisco Systems' Open Network Environment and Nicira's network virtualization platform.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SD-WAN applies similar technology to a wide area network (WAN).
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In addition to WAN use cases, SDN is also increasingly applied in telecom backbones, where it is paired with operational inventory and automation platforms to provide real-time visibility, service assurance, and simplified provisioning across multi-vendor networks.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The history of SDN principles can be traced back to the separation of the control and data planes first used in public switched telephone networks.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] This provided a manner of simplifying provisioning and management years before the architecture was used in data networks.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) began considering various ways to decouple the control and data forwarding functions in a proposed interface standard published in 2004 named Forwarding and Control Element Separation (ForCES).
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The ForCES Working Group also proposed a companion SoftRouter architecture.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Additional early standards from the IETF that pursued separating control from data planes include the Linux Netlink as an IP services protocol, and a path computation element (PCE)-based architecture.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] These early attempts failed to gain traction.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] One reason is that many in the Internet community viewed separating control from data to be risky, especially given the potential for failure in the control plane.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Another reason is that vendors were concerned that creating standard application programming interfaces (APIs) between the control and data planes would result in increased competition.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In 2006 a young startup was founded around SDN style network topology and submitted a collection of SDN patents in 2007.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The use of open-source software in these separated architectures traces its roots to the Ethane project at Stanford's computer science department.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Ethane's simple switch design led to the creation of OpenFlow, and an API for OpenFlow was first created in 2008.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In that same year, NOX, an operating system for networks, was created.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SDN research included emulators such as vSDNEmul, EstiNet, and Mininet.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Work on OpenFlow continued at Stanford, including with the creation of testbeds to evaluate the use of the protocol in a single campus network, as well as across the WAN as a backbone for connecting multiple campuses.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In academic settings, there were several research and production networks based on OpenFlow switches from NEC and Hewlett-Packard, as well as those based on Quanta Computer white-boxes starting in about 2009.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Beyond academia, the first deployments were by Nicira in 2010 to control OVS from Onix, codeveloped with NTT and Google.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] A notable deployment was Google's B4 in 2012.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Later, Google announced the first OpenFlow/Onix deployments in is datacenters.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Another large deployment exists at China Mobile.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The Open Networking Foundation was founded in 2011 to promote SDN and OpenFlow.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] At the 2014 Interop and Tech Field Day, software-defined networking was demonstrated by Avaya using shortest-path bridging (IEEE 802.1aq) and OpenStack as an automated campus, extending automation from the data center to the end device and removing manual provisioning from service delivery.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SDN architectures decouple network control (control plane) and forwarding (data plane) functions, enabling the network control to become directly programmable and the underlying infrastructure to be abstracted from applications and network services.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The OpenFlow protocol is one of the protocols used in SDN technologies.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The explosion of mobile devices and content, server virtualization, and the advent of cloud services are among the trends driving the networking industry to re-examine traditional network architectures.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Many conventional networks are hierarchical, built with tiers of Ethernet switches arranged in a tree structure.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] This design made sense when client-server computing was dominant, but such a static architecture may be ill-suited to the dynamic computing and storage needs of today's enterprise data centers, campuses, and carrier environments.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Within the enterprise data center, traffic patterns have changed significantly.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] At the same time, users are changing network traffic patterns as they push for access to corporate content and applications from any type of device, connecting from anywhere, at any time.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] model, which may include a private cloud, public cloud, or some mix of both, resulting in additional traffic across the wide-area network.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Users are increasingly employing mobile personal devices such as smartphones, tablets, and notebooks to access the corporate network.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] IT is under pressure to accommodate these personal devices in a fine-grained manner while protecting corporate data and intellectual property and meeting compliance mandates.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Enterprises have enthusiastically embraced both public and private cloud services, resulting in unprecedented growth of these services.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Many enterprise businesses want the agility to access applications, infrastructure and other IT resources on demand and discretely.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] IT planning for cloud services must be performed in an environment of increased security, compliance and auditing requirements, along with business reorganizations, consolidations and mergers that can rapidly change assumptions.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Providing self-service provisioning, whether in a private or public cloud, requires elastic scaling of computing, storage and network resources, ideally from a common viewpoint and with a common suite of tools.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] requires massive parallel processing on thousands of servers, all of which need direct connections to each other.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] is fueling a constant demand for additional network capacity in the data center.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Operators of hyperscale data center networks face the daunting task of scaling the network to previously unimaginable size, maintaining any-to-any connectivity within a limited budget.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] emerged, the need for larger data centers has increased the energy consumption of those facilities.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] applying existing routing techniques to dynamically adjust the network data plane to save energy.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Also techniques to improve control plane energy efficiency are being researched.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In addition, they may consume an abstracted view of the network for their internal decision-making purposes.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] An SDN Application consists of SDN application logic and one or more NBI drivers.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SDN applications may themselves expose another layer of abstracted network control, thus offering one or more higher-level NBIs through respective NBI agents.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The SDN controller is a logically centralized entity in charge of (i) translating the requirements from the SDN application layer down to the SDN datapaths and (ii) providing the SDN applications with an abstract view of the network (which may include statistics and events).
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] An SDN controller consists of one or more NBI agents, the SDN control logic, and the control to data-plane interface (CDPI) driver.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The SDN datapath is a logical network device that exposes visibility and uncontested control over its advertised forwarding and data processing capabilities.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The logical representation may encompass all or a subset of the capabilities.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath consists of a CDPI agent and a set of one or more traffic forwarding engines and zero or more traffic processing functions.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] These engines and functions may include simple forwarding between the datapath's external interfaces or internal traffic processing or termination functions.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] One or more SDN datapaths may be contained in a single (physical) network element—an integrated physical combination of communications resources, managed as a unit.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath may also be defined across multiple physical network elements.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The SDN CDPI is the interface defined between an SDN controller and an SDN datapath, which provides at least programmatic control of all forwarding operations, capabilities advertisement, statistics reporting, and event notification.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] One value of SDN lies in the expectation that the CDPI is implemented in an open, vendor-neutral and interoperable way.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SDN NBIs are interfaces between SDN applications and SDN controllers and typically provide abstract network views and enable direct expression of network behavior and requirements.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] This may occur at any level of abstraction and across different sets of functionality.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The implementation of the SDN control plane can follow a centralized, hierarchical, or decentralized design.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Initial SDN control plane proposals focused on a centralized solution, where a single control entity had a global view of the network.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] While this simplifies the implementation of the control logic, it has scalability limitations as the size and dynamics of the network increase.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] To overcome these limitations, hierarchical and distributed approaches have been proposed.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In hierarchical solutions, controllers operate on a partitioned network view, while decisions that require network-wide knowledge are taken by a logically centralized root controller.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In distributed approaches, controllers operate on their local view or they may exchange synchronization messages to enhance their knowledge.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Distributed solutions are more suitable for supporting adaptive SDN applications.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] A key issue when designing a distributed SDN control plane is to decide on the number and placement of control entities.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] An important parameter to consider while doing so is the propagation delay between the controllers and the network devices, especially in the context of large networks.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Other objectives that have been considered involve control path reliability, fault tolerance, and application requirements.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In SDN, the data plane is responsible for processing data-carrying packets using a set of rules specified by the control plane.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The data plane may be implemented in physical hardware switches or in software, such as Open vSwitch.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The memory capacity of hardware switches may limit the number of rules that can be stored whereas software implementations may have higher capacity.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Flow table entries may be populated in a proactive, reactive, or hybrid fashion.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In the proactive mode, the controller populates flow table entries for all possible traffic matches for this switch in advance.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] This mode can be compared with typical routing table entries today, where all static entries are installed ahead of time.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Following this, no request is sent to the controller since all incoming flows will find a matching entry.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] A major advantage in proactive mode is that all packets are forwarded at line rate (considering all flow table entries in TCAM) and no delay is added.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In the reactive mode, entries are populated on demand.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] If a packet arrives without a corresponding match rule in the flow table, the SDN agent sends a request to the controller for further instruction.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The controller examines the SDN agent requests and provides instructions, installing a rule in the flow table for the corresponding packet if necessary.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The hybrid mode uses the low-latency proactive forwarding mode for a portion of traffic while relying on the flexibility of reactive mode processing for the remaining traffic.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Software-defined mobile networking (SDMN) is an approach to the design of mobile networks where all protocol-specific features are implemented in software, maximizing the use of generic and commodity hardware and software in both the core network and radio access network.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] It is proposed as an extension of SDN paradigm to incorporate mobile network specific functionalities.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Since 3GPP Rel.14, a Control User Plane Separation was introduced in the Mobile Core Network architectures with the PFCP protocol.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] An SD-WAN is a WAN managed using the principles of software-defined networking.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The main driver of SD-WAN is to lower WAN costs using more affordable and commercially available leased lines, as an alternative or partial replacement of more expensive MPLS lines.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Control and management are administered separately from the hardware, with central controllers allowing for easier configuration and administration.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] An SD-LAN is a Local area network (LAN) built around the principles of software-defined networking, though there are key differences in topology, network security, application visibility and control, management and quality of service.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SD-LAN decouples control, management and data planes to enable a policy-driven architecture for wired and wireless LANs.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SD-LANs are characterized by their use of a cloud management system and wireless connectivity without the presence of a physical controller.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SDN architecture may enable, facilitate or enhance network-related security applications due to the controller's central view of the network, and its capacity to modify behavior or the data plane at any time.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The security implications of SDN architecture remain under study.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Several research works on SDN have already investigated security applications built upon the SDN controller, with different aims in mind.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Distributed denial of service (DDoS) detection and mitigation, as well as botnet and worm propagation, are some concrete use cases of such applications.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Proposed applications periodically collect network statistics from the forwarding plane of the network in a standardized manner (e.g., using OpenFlow), and then apply classification algorithms on those statistics in order to detect any network anomalies.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] If an anomaly is detected, the application instructs the controller how to reprogram the data plane in order to mitigate it.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Another kind of security application leverages the SDN controller by implementing some moving target defense (MTD) algorithms.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] MTD algorithms are typically used to make any attack on a given system or network more difficult than usual by periodically hiding or changing key properties of that system or network.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In traditional networks, implementing MTD algorithms is not a trivial task since it is difficult to build a central authority able to determine, for each part of the system to be protected, which key properties are hidden or changed.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In an SDN network, such tasks become more straightforward thanks to the centrality of the controller.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] One application can, for example, periodically assign virtual IPs to hosts within the network, and the mapping of virtual IP to real IP is then performed by the controller.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Another application can simulate some fake opened/closed/filtered ports on random hosts in the network in order to add significant noise during scanning performed by an attacker.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Additional value regarding security in SDN-enabled networks can also be gained using FlowVisor and FlowChecker.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The former tries to use a single hardware forwarding plane sharing multiple separated logical networks.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Following this approach, the same hardware resources can be used for production and development purposes as well as separating monitoring, configuration and Internet traffic, where each scenario can have its own logical topology, which is called a slice.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] In conjunction with this approach, FlowChecker realizes the validation of new OpenFlow rules that are deployed by users using their own slice.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SDN controller applications are mostly deployed in large-scale scenarios, which requires comprehensive checks of possible programming errors.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] A system to do this called NICE was described in 2012.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Introducing an overarching security architecture requires a comprehensive and protracted approach to SDN.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Since it was introduced, designers are looking at possible ways to secure SDN that do not compromise scalability.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] One architecture called SN-SECA (SDN+NFV) Security Architecture.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Distributed applications that run across datacenters usually replicate data for the purpose of synchronization, fault resiliency, load balancing and getting data closer to users (which reduces latency to users and increases their perceived throughput).
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Also, many applications, such as Hadoop, replicate data within a datacenter across multiple racks to increase fault tolerance and make data recovery easier.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] All of these operations require data delivery from one machine or datacenter to multiple machines or datacenters.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] The process of reliably delivering data from one machine to multiple machines is referred to as Reliable Group Data Delivery (RGDD).
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SDN switches can be used for RGDD via installation of rules that allow forwarding to multiple outgoing ports.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] For example, OpenFlow provides support for Group Tables since version 1.1 which makes this possible.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Using SDN, a central controller can carefully and intelligently setup forwarding trees for RGDD.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Such trees can be built while paying attention to network congestion/load status to improve performance.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] For example, MCTCP is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside datacenters that relies on regular and structured topologies of datacenter networks while DCCast and QuickCast are approaches for fast and efficient data and content replication across datacenters over private WANs.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Network Function Virtualization, or NFV for short, is a concept that complements SDN.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] NFV separates software from hardware to enable flexible network deployment and dynamic operation.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] NFV deployments typically use commodity servers to run network services software versions that previously were hardware-based.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] These software-based services that run in an NFV environment are called Virtual Network Functions (VNF).
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SDN-NFV hybrid program was provided for high efficiency, elastic and scalable capabilities NFV aimed at accelerating service innovation and provisioning using standard IT virtualization technologies.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] SDN provides the agility of controlling the generic forwarding devices such as the routers and switches by using SDN controllers.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] On the other hand, NFV agility is provided for the network applications by using virtualized servers.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] It is entirely possible to implement a virtualized network function (VNF) as a standalone entity using existing networking and orchestration paradigms.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] However, there are inherent benefits in leveraging SDN concepts to implement and manage an NFV infrastructure, particularly when looking at the management and orchestration of VNFs, and that's why multivendor platforms are being defined that incorporate SDN and NFV in concerted ecosystems.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Deep packet inspection (DPI) provides network with application-awareness, while SDN provides applications with network-awareness.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] Although SDN will radically change the generic network architectures, it should cope with working with traditional network architectures to offer high interoperability.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] When using an SDN based model for transmitting multimedia traffic, an important aspect to take account is the QoE estimation.
[src:network-automation/software-defined-networking] To estimate the QoE, first we have to be able to classify the traffic and then, it's recommended that the system can solve critical problems on its own by analyzing the traffic.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] ZTP saves configuration time while reducing errors.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] The process can also be used to update existing systems using scripts.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] Research has shown that ZTP systems allow for faster provisioning versus manual provisioning.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] The global market for ZTP services was estimated to be $2.1 Billion in 2021.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] In April 2019, the Internet Engineering Task Force published RFC 8572 Secure Zero Touch Provisioning (SZTP) as a Proposed Standard.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] The FIDO Alliance published FIDO Device Onboard version 1.0 in December 2020, and followed up with a FIDO Device Onboard version 1.1 in April 2022.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] Several FDO "app notes" augment this specification.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] FIDO Device Onboard is also a ZTP type protocol.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] One application of the technology is to improve delivery of cloud computing services.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] The concept has been particularly influential for information technology when paired with mobile device management.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] Repetitive processes that can be automated and streamlined include configuring settings; collecting inventory details; deploying apps; managing licenses; and implementing security policy, including password management and wiping remote devices.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] A basic ZTP system requires a network device that supports ZTP, a server that supports Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) or Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP), and a file server.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] When a ZTP-enabled device is powered on, the device's boot file sets up configuration parameters.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] A switch then sends a request using DHCP or TFTP to get the device's configuration file from a central location.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] The file then runs and configures ports, IP addresses and other server parameters for each location.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] A similar concept is the zero-touch network, which integrates zero-touch provisioning with automation, artificial intelligence and machine learning.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] In December 2017, the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) formed the Zero-touch network and Service Management group (ZSM) to accelerate development and standardization of the technology.
[src:network-automation/zero-touch-provisioning] In the summer of 2019, the group published a series of documents defining ZSM requirements, reference architecture and terminology.
